1
00:01:39,263 --> 00:01:43,393
<i>My father's name was John Kinsella.</i>
<i>It's an Irish name.</i>

2
00:01:44,018 --> 00:01:46,270
<i>He was born in North Dakota in 1896...</i>

3
00:01:46,396 --> 00:01:47,939
<i>...and never saw a big city...</i>

4
00:01:48,064 --> 00:01:51,317
<i>...until he came back from France in 1918.</i>

5
00:01:51,984 --> 00:01:55,863
<i>He settled in Chicago, where he learned</i>
<i>to live and die with the White Sox.</i>

6
00:01:56,364 --> 00:01:59,283
<i>Died a little</i>
<i>when they lost the 1919 World Series...</i>

7
00:01:59,992 --> 00:02:02,745
<i>...died a lot the following summer</i>
<i>when eight teammates...</i>

8
00:02:02,870 --> 00:02:05,123
<i>...were accused of throwing that Series.</i>

9
00:02:05,456 --> 00:02:08,710
<i>He played some in the minors,</i>
<i>but nothing came of it.</i>

10
00:02:09,293 --> 00:02:11,212
<i>Moved to Brooklyn in '35...</i>

11
00:02:11,546 --> 00:02:13,548
<i>...married Mom in '38...</i>

12
00:02:13,673 --> 00:02:16,175
<i>...was already an old man</i>
<i>at the naval yards...</i>

13
00:02:16,384 --> 00:02:18,386
<i>...when I was born in 1952.</i>

14
00:02:19,345 --> 00:02:21,222
<i>My name's Ray Kinsella.</i>

15
00:02:21,597 --> 00:02:26,060
<i>Mom died when I was 3,</i>
<i>and I suppose Dad did the best he could.</i>

16
00:02:26,352 --> 00:02:31,482
<i>Instead of Mother Goose, I was put to bed</i>
<i>to stories of Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig...</i>

17
00:02:31,607 --> 00:02:34,152
<i>...and the great Shoeless Joe Jackson.</i>

18
00:02:34,777 --> 00:02:38,489
<i>Dad was a Yankees fan then,</i>
<i>so I rooted for Brooklyn.</i>

19
00:02:38,614 --> 00:02:43,327
<i>But in '58, the Dodgers moved away,</i>
<i>so we had to find other reasons to fight.</i>

20
00:02:43,536 --> 00:02:44,579
<i>We did.</i>

21
00:02:44,787 --> 00:02:46,789
<i>When it came time to go to college...</i>

22
00:02:46,914 --> 00:02:49,292
<i>...I picked the farthest</i>
<i>from home I could find.</i>

23
00:02:50,793 --> 00:02:54,672
<i>This drove him up the wall,</i>
<i>which, I suppose, was the point.</i>

24
00:02:55,256 --> 00:02:59,302
<i>Officially my major was English,</i>
<i>but really it was the '60s.</i>

25
00:02:59,802 --> 00:03:02,180
<i>I marched, I smoked some grass...</i>

26
00:03:02,472 --> 00:03:05,850
<i>...I tried to like sitar music,</i>
<i>and I met Annie.</i>

27
00:03:06,726 --> 00:03:10,104
<i>The only thing we had in common</i>
<i>was that she came from Iowa...</i>

28
00:03:10,229 --> 00:03:12,065
<i>...and I'd once heard of Iowa.</i>

29
00:03:13,107 --> 00:03:15,318
<i>After graduation,</i>
<i>we moved to the Midwest...</i>

30
00:03:15,443 --> 00:03:18,112
<i>...and stayed with her family</i>
<i>as long as we could.</i>

31
00:03:18,237 --> 00:03:20,156
<i>Almost a full afternoon.</i>

32
00:03:21,115 --> 00:03:23,910
<i>Annie and I got married in June of '74.</i>

33
00:03:24,285 --> 00:03:26,120
<i>Dad died that fall.</i>

34
00:03:26,788 --> 00:03:29,082
<i>A few years later, Karin was born.</i>

35
00:03:29,207 --> 00:03:31,376
<i>She smelled weird,</i>
<i>but we loved her anyway.</i>

36
00:03:32,085 --> 00:03:35,963
<i>Then Annie got the crazy idea</i>
<i>that she could talk me into buying a farm.</i>

37
00:03:37,090 --> 00:03:40,677
<i>I'm 36 years old, I love my family,</i>
<i>I love baseball...</i>

38
00:03:40,802 --> 00:03:43,388
<i>...and I'm about to become a farmer.</i>

39
00:03:44,013 --> 00:03:46,224
<i>But until I heard the voice...</i>

40
00:03:46,766 --> 00:03:50,019
<i>...I'd never done a crazy thing</i>
<i>in my whole life.</i>

41
00:04:27,348 --> 00:04:30,685
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

42
00:04:49,662 --> 00:04:52,999
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

43
00:05:01,841 --> 00:05:03,217
Hey, Annie!

44
00:05:03,760 --> 00:05:06,471
- Annie, what was that?
- What was what?

45
00:05:08,681 --> 00:05:11,142
That voice just now. What was it?

46
00:05:14,520 --> 00:05:16,356
We didn't hear anything.

47
00:05:20,360 --> 00:05:21,611
All right.

48
00:05:24,864 --> 00:05:28,201
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

49
00:05:33,623 --> 00:05:36,793
- Okay, you must have heard that!
- Sorry.

50
00:05:37,293 --> 00:05:39,379
Hey, come on in to dinner.

51
00:05:39,879 --> 00:05:41,422
Let's go, pumpkin.

52
00:06:01,150 --> 00:06:03,403
Is there a sound truck on the highway?

53
00:06:03,528 --> 00:06:06,406
Nope. Hey, Karin, dinner's ready!

54
00:06:07,448 --> 00:06:09,826
- Kids with a radio?
- Nope.

55
00:06:10,702 --> 00:06:14,330
- Are you really hearing voices?
- Just one.

56
00:06:15,790 --> 00:06:17,250
What did it say?

57
00:06:18,751 --> 00:06:20,878
"If you build it, he will come."

58
00:06:24,132 --> 00:06:27,760
- If you build what, who will come?
- He didn't say.

59
00:06:29,220 --> 00:06:32,473
- I hate it when that happens.
- Me, too.

60
00:06:46,988 --> 00:06:50,324
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

61
00:07:04,255 --> 00:07:07,133
Build what? What is this?

62
00:07:11,888 --> 00:07:13,639
It's okay, honey.

63
00:07:14,557 --> 00:07:17,101
I'm just talking to the corn field.

64
00:07:21,522 --> 00:07:23,816
<i>Anyway, I was walking</i>
<i>down along the street...</i>

65
00:07:23,941 --> 00:07:26,235
<i>...and I heard this voice saying...</i>

66
00:07:26,361 --> 00:07:28,029
<i>..."Good evening, Mr. Dowd."</i>

67
00:07:28,154 --> 00:07:30,573
<i>Well, I turned around...</i>

68
00:07:31,574 --> 00:07:35,286
<i>...and here was this big six-foot rabbit</i>
<i>leaning up against the lamppost.</i>

69
00:07:39,749 --> 00:07:43,961
- Why did you do that? It was funny.
- Trust me. It's not funny.

70
00:07:44,212 --> 00:07:46,589
The man is sick. Very sick.

71
00:07:46,714 --> 00:07:49,008
Honey, get your book bag. Let's go!

72
00:07:49,133 --> 00:07:53,012
I'll take her today.
I've got some errands to do in town.

73
00:07:53,638 --> 00:07:54,681
Far-out.

74
00:07:59,727 --> 00:08:04,107
- What if the voice calls while you're gone?
- Take a message.

75
00:08:04,816 --> 00:08:06,901
- 'Bye.
- 'Bye.

76
00:08:07,276 --> 00:08:08,319
'Bye.

77
00:08:10,571 --> 00:08:13,116
In all those years, did you ever...

78
00:08:13,658 --> 00:08:16,994
It's just I've heard
that sometimes farmers in the field...

79
00:08:17,120 --> 00:08:19,622
They hear things. You know, voices.

80
00:08:19,747 --> 00:08:23,835
- You hearing voices?
- No. It's just I heard some farmers do.

81
00:08:23,960 --> 00:08:28,381
I, of course, don't, so I was wondering
if I was doing something wrong.

82
00:08:30,466 --> 00:08:33,136
Did you ever hear voices out there?

83
00:08:33,261 --> 00:08:36,764
- Who's hearing voices?
- Ray is. Out in the fields.

84
00:08:36,889 --> 00:08:38,266
No, I'm not.

85
00:08:39,017 --> 00:08:40,018
I'm...

86
00:08:43,062 --> 00:08:44,605
Noises.

87
00:08:44,897 --> 00:08:46,983
That darned tractor...

88
00:08:47,817 --> 00:08:51,446
I'm just going to get some 3-in-1oil.
That ought to do it.

89
00:08:52,113 --> 00:08:54,866
Nice talking to you.

90
00:09:22,643 --> 00:09:25,438
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

91
00:09:25,772 --> 00:09:28,900
All right, that's it! Who the...

92
00:09:30,276 --> 00:09:32,987
Who are you? What do you want from me?

93
00:09:33,154 --> 00:09:34,197
Son of a bitch.

94
00:09:34,322 --> 00:09:37,658
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

95
00:09:39,577 --> 00:09:41,204
If you build it...

96
00:09:49,837 --> 00:09:51,381
If you build it...

97
00:09:58,680 --> 00:09:59,931
...he will come.

98
00:10:28,167 --> 00:10:30,920
You don't suppose
this is like an acid flashback?

99
00:10:32,171 --> 00:10:33,339
I never took acid.

100
00:10:33,423 --> 00:10:36,718
Maybe you will someday.
It's like a flash-forward.

101
00:10:37,593 --> 00:10:39,137
Annie, there's more.

102
00:10:39,220 --> 00:10:41,931
Honey, why don't you eat a little bit?

103
00:10:44,100 --> 00:10:47,186
I think I know what
"If you build it, he will come" means.

104
00:10:47,311 --> 00:10:49,981
Why do I not think
this is such a good thing?

105
00:10:50,815 --> 00:10:54,902
I think it means
that if I build a baseball field out there...

106
00:10:55,862 --> 00:10:59,699
...Shoeless Joe Jackson
will come back and play ball again.

107
00:11:01,451 --> 00:11:02,910
You're kidding?

108
00:11:10,793 --> 00:11:11,794
You're kidding.

109
00:11:14,797 --> 00:11:17,216
Boy, I thought my family was crazy...

110
00:11:17,342 --> 00:11:19,719
...but this is the craziest thing
I've ever heard.

111
00:11:19,844 --> 00:11:21,304
I know it's totally nuts.

112
00:11:21,387 --> 00:11:25,266
- I mean, Shoeless Joe!
- He's dead. Died in '51. He's dead.

113
00:11:25,391 --> 00:11:28,061
- They suspended him, right?
- Right.

114
00:11:28,519 --> 00:11:31,773
- He's still dead?
- As far as I know.

115
00:11:35,443 --> 00:11:37,612
Did you know Babe Ruth copied his swing?

116
00:11:39,739 --> 00:11:41,908
If I did, I've forgotten it.

117
00:11:47,747 --> 00:11:50,708
He was supposed to be
so graceful and agile.

118
00:11:51,417 --> 00:11:54,128
I'd actually like to see him play again...

119
00:11:54,253 --> 00:11:57,507
...to let him play, to right an old wrong.

120
00:11:57,632 --> 00:12:00,301
Wait. Wait a minute.

121
00:12:02,637 --> 00:12:07,016
- Are you actually thinking of doing this?
- No.

122
00:12:08,393 --> 00:12:12,063
I can't think of one good reason
why I should, but...

123
00:12:20,363 --> 00:12:24,158
I'm 36. I have a wife,
a child, and a mortgage...

124
00:12:24,283 --> 00:12:27,161
...and I'm scared to death
I'm turning into my father.

125
00:12:28,621 --> 00:12:30,540
What does he have to do with all this?

126
00:12:32,542 --> 00:12:35,211
I never forgave him for getting old.

127
00:12:38,047 --> 00:12:40,925
By the time he was as old as I am now...

128
00:12:41,426 --> 00:12:43,177
...he was ancient.

129
00:12:45,513 --> 00:12:50,643
He must have had dreams,
but he never did anything about them.

130
00:12:51,894 --> 00:12:55,106
For all I know,
he may have even heard voices, too...

131
00:12:56,441 --> 00:12:59,110
...but he sure didn't listen to them.

132
00:12:59,360 --> 00:13:03,406
The man never did one spontaneous thing
in all the years I knew him.

133
00:13:04,782 --> 00:13:07,952
I'm afraid of that happening to me...

134
00:13:09,620 --> 00:13:12,331
...and something tells me
this may be my last chance...

135
00:13:12,457 --> 00:13:14,417
...to do something about it.

136
00:13:17,628 --> 00:13:19,797
I want to build that field.

137
00:13:22,133 --> 00:13:23,718
Do you think I'm crazy?

138
00:13:24,844 --> 00:13:25,970
Yes.

139
00:13:30,308 --> 00:13:34,896
But I also think
if you really feel you should do this...

140
00:13:37,482 --> 00:13:39,609
...then you should do it.

141
00:13:53,915 --> 00:13:57,794
- What the hell is he doing?
- He's plowing under his corn.

142
00:13:58,336 --> 00:13:59,295
Why?

143
00:14:05,468 --> 00:14:09,097
Ty Cobb called him
the greatest left fielder of all time.

144
00:14:09,347 --> 00:14:13,393
He said his glove
was the place where triples go to die.

145
00:14:13,851 --> 00:14:15,895
- Could he hit?
- Could he hit?

146
00:14:16,020 --> 00:14:18,815
Lifetime average .356,
third highest in history.

147
00:14:19,107 --> 00:14:20,900
Why'd they call him "Shoeless Joe"?

148
00:14:21,901 --> 00:14:23,277
When he was in the minors...

149
00:14:23,403 --> 00:14:26,197
...he bought a new pair of spikes
and hurt his feet.

150
00:14:26,322 --> 00:14:30,076
<i>In the 6th inning, he took them off</i>
<i>and played in his socks.</i>

151
00:14:30,201 --> 00:14:34,622
<i>The players kidded him, called him</i>
<i>"Shoeless Joe" and the name stuck.</i>

152
00:14:35,540 --> 00:14:37,208
He's going to lose his farm.

153
00:14:37,333 --> 00:14:38,501
Damned fool.

154
00:14:38,626 --> 00:14:41,879
<i>Then in 1919,</i>
<i>his team the Chicago White Sox...</i>

155
00:14:42,005 --> 00:14:44,090
<i>...threw the World Series.</i>

156
00:14:44,215 --> 00:14:47,844
- <i>What's "threw"?</i>
- <i>It means they lost it on purpose.</i>

157
00:14:47,969 --> 00:14:50,013
<i>Gamblers paid them to.</i>

158
00:14:50,138 --> 00:14:52,348
<i>Except Shoeless Joe.</i>

159
00:14:52,682 --> 00:14:56,269
<i>He did take their money,</i>
<i>but nobody ever proved he did one thing...</i>

160
00:14:56,394 --> 00:14:57,979
<i>...to lose those games.</i>

161
00:14:59,522 --> 00:15:03,568
If he threw it, how do you explain
that he hit .375 for the Series...

162
00:15:03,693 --> 00:15:05,486
...and committed no errors?

163
00:15:05,611 --> 00:15:06,612
I can't.

164
00:15:06,738 --> 00:15:09,282
Twelve hits including
the Series' only home run...

165
00:15:09,407 --> 00:15:11,701
...and they said he's trying to lose?

166
00:15:11,826 --> 00:15:12,952
It's ridiculous.

167
00:15:13,619 --> 00:15:16,581
<i>The commissioner of baseball</i>
<i>suspended eight of the players...</i>

168
00:15:16,706 --> 00:15:19,709
<i>...including the great Shoeless Joe</i>
<i>Jackson, for life.</i>

169
00:15:19,834 --> 00:15:21,461
<i>What's "suspend"?</i>

170
00:15:22,545 --> 00:15:25,715
<i>It means they never</i>
<i>let him play the game again.</i>

171
00:15:28,551 --> 00:15:30,636
My father said he saw him years later...

172
00:15:30,762 --> 00:15:35,058
...playing under a made-up name
in some 10th-rate league in Carolina.

173
00:15:35,391 --> 00:15:38,686
He'd put on 50 pounds,
and his spring was gone from his step...

174
00:15:38,811 --> 00:15:40,688
...but he could still hit.

175
00:15:41,606 --> 00:15:44,984
Dad used to say
nobody could hit like Shoeless Joe.

176
00:15:46,402 --> 00:15:49,238
I think that's the first time
I've ever seen you smile...

177
00:15:49,364 --> 00:15:51,741
...when you mentioned your father.

178
00:16:05,588 --> 00:16:08,883
I have just created something
totally illogical.

179
00:16:12,512 --> 00:16:14,722
That's what I like about it.

180
00:16:17,225 --> 00:16:19,018
Am I completely nuts?

181
00:16:21,813 --> 00:16:23,481
Not completely.

182
00:16:24,857 --> 00:16:27,318
It's a good baseball field, Ray.

183
00:16:28,236 --> 00:16:30,571
It's kind of pretty, isn't it?

184
00:16:53,511 --> 00:16:54,804
Any sign?

185
00:16:57,640 --> 00:17:00,351
Something's going to happen out there.

186
00:17:01,102 --> 00:17:02,562
I can feel it.

187
00:17:22,290 --> 00:17:25,960
<i>So, for the veteran southpaw,</i>
<i>his summer of woes continues.</i>

188
00:17:26,210 --> 00:17:28,087
<i>That's four straight hits in the inning.</i>

189
00:17:28,212 --> 00:17:30,923
Daddy, what's a "southpaw"?

190
00:17:33,634 --> 00:17:35,845
It means a left-handed pitcher, honey.

191
00:17:37,847 --> 00:17:40,350
- So how bad is it?
- Well.

192
00:17:41,976 --> 00:17:46,064
Considering how much less acreage
we have for corn, I say we'll probably...

193
00:17:47,523 --> 00:17:49,400
...almost break even.

194
00:17:53,571 --> 00:17:56,366
We used up all our savings on that field.

195
00:17:56,991 --> 00:17:59,577
- Daddy?
- Just a minute, Karin.

196
00:18:04,248 --> 00:18:07,293
So what are you saying?
We can't keep the field?

197
00:18:10,129 --> 00:18:12,799
Makes it real hard to keep the farm.

198
00:18:17,470 --> 00:18:19,681
- Daddy.
- In a minute, Karin!

199
00:18:20,932 --> 00:18:23,017
There's a man out there on your lawn.

200
00:19:10,815 --> 00:19:14,360
I'll put up some coffee.
Why don't you go on outside?

201
00:21:12,437 --> 00:21:13,563
Sorry.

202
00:21:17,233 --> 00:21:19,402
I'll get some out there.

203
00:21:50,099 --> 00:21:51,225
Hi.

204
00:21:53,227 --> 00:21:54,479
Ray Kinsella.

205
00:21:56,731 --> 00:21:58,274
Joe Jackson.

206
00:22:26,469 --> 00:22:29,347
I bet it's good to be playing again.

207
00:22:36,145 --> 00:22:38,606
Getting thrown out of baseball...

208
00:22:40,108 --> 00:22:42,944
...was like having part of me amputated.

209
00:22:44,862 --> 00:22:47,156
I've heard that old men wake up...

210
00:22:47,281 --> 00:22:51,369
...and scratch itchy legs
that have been dust for over 50 years.

211
00:22:52,245 --> 00:22:53,705
That was me.

212
00:22:55,289 --> 00:22:57,291
I'd wake up at night...

213
00:22:58,376 --> 00:23:01,504
...with the smell
of the ballpark in my nose...

214
00:23:02,380 --> 00:23:05,383
...with the cool of the grass on my feet...

215
00:23:07,677 --> 00:23:09,762
...the thrill of the grass.

216

00:23:17,520 --> 00:23:18,980
Can you pitch?

217
00:23:20,982 --> 00:23:22,108
Yeah.

218
00:23:23,860 --> 00:23:25,028
Not bad.

219
00:23:41,044 --> 00:23:44,630
- Don't we need a catcher?
- Not if you get it near the plate.

220
00:23:46,674 --> 00:23:47,800
Right.

221
00:24:00,480 --> 00:24:02,940
I'm pitching to Shoeless Joe Jackson.

222
00:24:12,075 --> 00:24:13,076
Nice hit.

223
00:24:28,299 --> 00:24:30,009
See if you can hit my curve.

224
00:24:39,936 --> 00:24:44,107
- You can hit the curve ball.
- Put one right here.

225
00:24:46,317 --> 00:24:47,443
Right.

226
00:25:01,457 --> 00:25:03,418
Right, you're a low-ball hitter.

227
00:25:04,085 --> 00:25:06,295
Man, I did love this game.

228
00:25:08,756 --> 00:25:11,050
I'd have played for food money.

229
00:25:12,301 --> 00:25:16,139
It was the game, the sounds, the smells.

230
00:25:18,349 --> 00:25:22,812
Did you ever hold a ball
or a glove to your face?

231
00:25:23,896 --> 00:25:24,897
Yeah.

232
00:25:25,481 --> 00:25:29,402
I used to love traveling on the trains
from town to town.

